1610":"1610","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1541":"1541","1585":"1585","about 1540":"about 1540","1517":"1517","1549":"1549","Farnworth, Lancashire, England":"Farnworth, Lancashire, England","Standish, Lancashire, England":"Standish, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rothwell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Rowell  . This name was brought to Ireland (Meath) from England in the 17th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Rowell","meanings":["English:","habitational name principally from Rothwell (Yorkshire), but Rothwell in Lincolnshire and Northamptonshire also gave rise to surnames. The placenames derive from Old English <i>roth</i> ‘clearing’ + <i>wella</i> ‘well, spring, stream’.","habitational name from Rowell in Chudleigh (Devon), named with Old English <i>rūh</i> ‘rough’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’. The name may have been confused with   Roll  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Adami","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical.  See  <b>Adam</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Adam","meanings":["Hebrew: The Scripture name, in Hebrew, Adham, signifying 'man;' literally earthy, red earth; Rudolph, however, says the name in Ethiopic means ' to be fair, beautiful.' Hence the nurse-name Addy, little Adam."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":32,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":41,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705207,"age":68,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705208,"age":70,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705212,"age":103,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Adami Rothwell was born about 1517, in Lancashire, England, his father, James Rothwell, was 38 and his mother, Mary Fitzpatrick, was 36. He married Elizabeth Hulton about 1540, in Farnworth, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1517–":"umbes 1517–Surnud","1517–Male":"1517–Surnud","1523–Female":"1523–Surnud","1541–1610":"1541–1610","1480–1517":"1480–1517","1482–1560":"1482–1560","1560":"1560","1482":"1482","1480":"1480","1558":"1558","1523":"1523","about 1517":"umbes 1517","1610":"1610","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1541":"1541","1585":"1585","about 1540":"umbes 1540","1517":"1517","1549":"1549","Farnworth, Lancashire, England":"Farnworth, Lancashire, England","Standish, Lancashire, England":"Standish, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"about 1517–":"noin 1517–Kuollut","1517–Male":"1517–Kuollut","1523–Female":"1523–Kuollut","1541–1610":"1541–1610","1480–1517":"1480–1517","1482–1560":"1482–1560","1560":"1560","1482":"1482","1480":"1480","1558":"1558","1523":"1523","about 1517":"noin 1517","1610":"1610","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1541":"1541","1585":"1585","about 1540":"noin 1540","1517":"1517","1549":"1549","Farnworth, Lancashire, England":"Farnworth, Lancashire, England","Standish, Lancashire, England":"Standish, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"about 1517–":"environ 1517–Décédé","1517–Male":"1517–Décédé","1523–Female":"1523–Décédée","1541–1610":"1541–1610","1480–1517":"1480–1517","148